				I only troll this board occasionally now, and rarely post.  But I must now say that I agree completely with Illanae.  It is YOUR duty to parent your children, not Triton, not the internet, and not TV. <br>  <br> You blame your child's decent into offensiveness on Triton's webpage when there are literally THOUSANDS of free porn sites on the web that not only speak about anal rape but will allow a 12 year old child to view it himself.  Your child can see a woman sucking a dog's C*%^ on the internet and you bitch about Triton using the word F&amp;%* too excessively?  You have chosen the wrong subject for your assault. <br>  <br> The absolute largest problem in the world today is an increasing inability of people to accept responsibilities for THEIR actions.  WE ARE A PRODUCT OF OUR DECISIONS.  In many ways, our children are a product of our decisions.    <br>  <br> You child is a product of your decision to be a poor parent. <br>  <br> ________________________ <br>  <br> But, out of a desire to help ensure your child doesn't grow up to be in denial of his responsibilities like his parent(s), I feel obligated to offer parenting advice: <br>  <br>  <br> NEVER let your child do anything without discussing with him/her the results and ramifications of his action and the actions he witnessed.  You are ALWAYS your child's teacher.  If he is watching TV, you should be there discussing it with him or discuss it with him afterwards.  If he goes online, ditto.  It is your duty to discuss all topics with your child openly and maturely.  Listen to your child and try to understand what s/he is experiencing.  Then you can better &quot;mold&quot; your child to be a productive and happy individual in society. <br>  <br> There are some things your child should not be exposed to.  Certainly, the internet is something that should be severely regulated by you.  S/he should not be visiting porn sites, Triton's web page or even EQVault.  YOU should make the decision of what he views.  And once he views it, YOU should be the one responsible for educating him on why or how something is not right and why or how something can be MADE right. <br>  <br> No matter what you do or say, when your child sees or hears &quot;FUCK&quot;, he is going to repeat it.  Children mimic.  That is how they learn and adapt.  Your child would have seen or heard &quot;FUCK&quot; whether or not he visited Triton's web page.  It has always been and will always be your responsibility to know your child and impress upon him the importance of not disrespecting people by using that term.  It has never been and will never be Triton's responsibility, or the Internet's responsibility. <br>  <br> I think you should spend more time talking WITH your child instead of talking TO your child (or playing EQ).  And start taking responsibility for your actions, or lack thereof. <br> -------------------------- <br>  <br> Christianity is an amazing religion.  I too am a Christian.  In fact, my favorite two parts of the Christian faith are how Jesus taught to &quot;turn the other cheek&quot; and tolerance of people's differences.  Jesus did not walk into the Jews' homes and tell them he would seek to have them removed from Jerusalem because they lived in wealth while others starved.  And he did not pick up a rock and throw it at Mary.  What he did do was preach tolerance and understanding of others.  For only through understanding a person can another person convince him that his ways are in error. <br>  <br> So understand your child and teach him that his ways are in error. <br>  <br> God bless!		

